How_Calculated: Estimated number of all-cause deaths associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to modeled natural background. Estimate is calculated using the chronic all-cause mortality risk estimate from a comprehensive study by Krewski et al 2009.  The rate is the number of deaths attributable to PM2.5 among residents (30 years and older), divided by the population of residents (30 years and older) expressed as cases per 100,000 residents.
SourceDescription: New York City Bureau of Vital Statistics; United States Census

IndicatorName: PM2.5-Attributable Respiratory Hospitalizations (Adults 20 Yrs and Older)
How_Calculated: Estimate is based on the number of hospitalizations for respiratory causes associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to modeled natural background.  Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalizations for all respiratory causes from the Moolgavkar 2000 study conducted on Los Angeles residents between 20-64 years of age and the Zanobetti et al 2009 study in 26 US communities of residents over 65 years of age.  Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents over 20 years of Age.
SourceDescription: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS); US Census

IndicatorName: PM2.5-Attributable Respiratory Hospitalizations (Adults 20 Yrs and Older)

IndicatorName: PM2.5-Attributable Cardiovascular Hospitalizations (Adults 40 Yrs and Older)
How_Calculated: Estimate is based on the number of hospitalizations for cardiovascular causes associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to natural background (modeled air quality levels under no man-made air pollution emissions).  Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalizations for all cardiovascular causes from the Ito et al 2010 study conducted on New York City residents above 40 years of age.  Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents over 40 years of Age.
SourceDescription: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS); US Census
